This repository contains the complete submission for the DevOps Internship assignment, 
demonstrating practical skills in Linux server administration, containerization, 
automated monitoring, access control, and network security.

Task 1 — SSH Configuration & Secure Server Access
The first task involves provisioning a Linux server and establishing secure remote 
access using SSH key-based authentication. An Ed25519 key pair is generated on the 
local machine, the public key is deployed to the server, and password authentication 
is fully disabled in the SSH daemon configuration — ensuring that only authorized 
key holders can access the server.

Task 2 — Docker Installation & Web Application Deployment
This task covers installing Docker on the server and deploying a containerized web 
application. A custom Dockerfile is written using nginx:alpine as the base image, 
serving a personalized index.html page. The image is built locally and run as a 
detached container with the application exposed on port 8000, accessible via the 
server's IP address through any browser.

Task 3 — Automated Container Resource Monitoring
A bash script is created to capture real-time CPU and memory usage statistics from 
the running Docker container using docker stats. Each entry is timestamped and 
appended to a daily log file stored in /opt/container-monitor/logs/. The script is 
automated using a cron job configured to execute every minute, providing continuous 
and hands-free container monitoring.

Task 4 — Access Control & Log Security
A dedicated system user named monitor is created exclusively for monitoring 
operations. The monitoring directory /opt/container-monitor is created and its 
ownership is assigned to this user. Directory permissions are set to 700, granting 
full access to the monitor user while completely restricting access for all other 
users on the system. A verification script confirms that access control is correctly 
enforced.

Task 5 — Firewall Configuration with UFW
UFW is installed and configured with a secure rule set. SSH access is restricted 
exclusively to a specific trusted IP address, HTTP traffic on port 80 is permitted, 
and port 8000 is opened for the Docker web application. All other incoming traffic 
is denied by default, resulting in a hardened and minimal attack surface.
